    "body": "This now works! Thanks very much for your help. Seems most of the problems were due to the old version of iPython on the Mint repositories. \n\nFor those who have the same problem, here are the steps I went through to upgrade to the new version on Mint 15 and get the <code>custom.js</code> code from @Carreau working. \n\nFirst I uninstalled the old version of iPython:\n\n<code>sudo apt-get remove ipython-notebook python-matplotlib python-scipy python-pandas python-sympy python-nose</code>\n\n(Not sure if I needed to uninstall everything, but I just did the reverse of what I did to install it to make sure everything was back to 'mint' condition...).\n\nThen I downloaded <code>ipython-1.1.0.tar.gz</code> and ran:\n\n<code>tar -xzf ipython-1.1.0.tar.gz</code>\n\n...the <code>cd ipython-1.1.0</code>, and <code>sudo python setup.py install<code>, which appeared to run without errors.\n\nI then went back to my pre-existing notebooks, ran <code>ipython notebook --profile=nbserver</code>, which failed saying a module called <code>jinja2</code> was missing.\n\nTo install this, you need <code>easy_install</code>, which is part of <code>python-setuptools</code>:\n\n<code>sudo apt-get install python-setuptools</code>\n\n...followed by:\n\n<code>sudo easy_install Jinja2</code>\n\nAfter this, my notebook would start as normal. I like the newer interface! The old version would explain my initial confusion about the \"cell toolbar\", which I had initially assumed was some kind of background process, as it is not on the interface in the old 0.13 version.\n\nTo get @Carreau 's <code>custom.js</code> working, I created the file: <code>~/.config/ipython/profile_nbserver/static/custom/custom.js</code>, and placed the code above into it before restarting my notebook server.\n\n(NB: as mentioned above, this may be <code>~/.ipython/profile_nbserver/static/custom/custom.js</code> for some people....)\n\nAnd hey presto, there was an option to select \"android\" under \"Cell Toolbar\". When pressed, this opens the cell for editing. I haven't found that using shift-Return in the soft keyboard on Android works, but pressing the \"Play\" button on the toolbar performs the same function.\n\nMany thanks again for your time working this out @Carreau !\n"
  }
